YENAGOA – Academic and other activities have been paralysed at the Federal University, Otuoke (FUO) and the Bayelsa State-owned Niger Delta University (NDU) following the one-week warning strike started on Monday by the Non-Academic Staff Union (NASU) and the Senior Staff Association of Universities (SSANU). It was gathered on Tuesday that members of the NASU and the SSANU were staying away from work in compliance with the directive of the national secretariats of the two unions. Powered by RubiQube Ad Network A student of the FUO who identified herself simply as Happiness, said the workers’ action “is making things difficult for us students” and appealed to the two unions to “consider those of us who are poor students.” Mr. Kalizibe Joseph, the SSANU chairman, FUO chapter, described the impact of the strike in the university as total and comprehensive. He said that members of the unions were ready to carry out directives in the interest of the unions and the workers.